               <history>
                  <origin>Completed for <persName role="pat" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/71736800"
                     >Thomas Roebuck (1781–1819)</persName> in <origPlace
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7030776">Calcutta (Kolkata)</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Gregorian" when="1815">1815 CE</origDate>. A member of the
                     Asiatic Society Roebuck, authored <title>An English and Hindoostanee naval
                        dictionary of technical terms and sea phrases</title> (1811) and the
                     posthumously published <title>Proverbs, and Proverbial Phrases in the Persian
                        and Hindostanee Language</title> (1824).</origin>
                  <provenance><p>After Roebuck's death from fever in Calcutta in <date
                     calendar="#Gregorian" when="1819">1819</date>, his surviving family
                     apparently sold most of his oriental manuscripts through the <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                        >London</placeName> firm of <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/17541837"
                           key="person_17541837">Samuel Sotheby (1771–1842)</persName> on
                     <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1820-05-13">13 May 1820</date>;
                     however, this two-volume set does not appear in the catalogue, so the
                     circumstances under which it left Roebuck's possession and arrived in
                     Britain remain unclear.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently acquired by scholar <persName role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                        Bland (1803–1865)</persName> from an unknown source for his library at
                        Randalls Park, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735"
                           key="place_7011735">Leatherhead</placeName>. After his death, <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                              >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                                 ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                                 (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                                    role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                                    >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                                       calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date>, and moved to <orgName
                                          ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                                          Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                                             ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                                             >Wigan</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                     change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                        calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                        Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                        <placeName>Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
